      As another analogy to our current system, we set up a simplified example economy...<br/><br/>Business Owner Bob makes cars, hires employees, and sells cars. <br/>(for the sake of simplicity of the example, he is the only business, and Bob and his employees are the only citizens. Employees are paid enough to buy a car.) Bob has 10 employees. Bob gets the idea to automate production. The 10 employees are no longer have work as a result, but with the automated system, Bob is able to make 11 cars.<br/><br/>In our current system:<br/>The citizens, without work, are unable to afford cars. They sit around and do nothing. Bob has cars, but noone to buy them. As production costs money, Bob goes broke. The citizens are without work. The economy collapses (kind of like what's going on now.) Bob soon has no money since he can't sell, and everyone is out on the street.<br/><br/>In the Heinlein Heritage Check system:<br/>The citizens, without work, watch as Bob makes his cars. Once his cars are made, due to increase in production in the society, each of the citizens receives enough money to buy a car. They each buy a car, and Bob has enough money to continue to run his car making business (now completely automated.) With his newfound earnings, he notices the market is full on cars, and he doesn't need to sell anymore, so he puts his automated factory out on the market. The money for this is made available to all, but it floats among people for the time being. Bob, with his original production costs already covered, can build an icecream factory. The workers come work for him, and buy icecream and work for more money. The increase in production earns everyone more money. Some workers pool their resources and buy the factory. Now Bob has all profit, and the workers have their own car factory. The workers who bought the car factory can sell new cars as old ones break, and Bob, with the profits from the car factory being sold as well as his new money from the icecream factory, can start up two businesses. One selling houses, and another selling airplanes.<br/>And the cycle continues at an increasing rate.<br/><br/>To summarize, our current system, in a pretty standard and simplified situation, can't hold up, and quickly collapses (in the method of our current economic crisis). The Heinlein heritage check system, when presented with the problem (lots of 'bad' product) instead uses it as an advantage, and surges forward to a stronger economy.

                  
    </td>
  </tr>


